<body>

<div class="header-bar">
  <div class="header-tag">Research Plan</div>
  <div class="header-title">Next Loyalty Programme — UX Research Plan</div>
  <div class="header-sub">UXReactors 5D Pragmatic UX Framework · Moderated User Interviews · 2 Segments</div>
  <div class="header-meta">
    <div class="meta-item"><span class="lbl">Client</span><span class="val">Next plc</span></div>
    <div class="meta-item"><span class="lbl">Study Type</span><span class="val">Formative · Exploratory</span></div>
    <div class="meta-item"><span class="lbl">Methodology</span><span class="val">Moderated Remote Interviews</span></div>
    <div class="meta-item"><span class="lbl">Segments</span><span class="val">Customer · Store Associate</span></div>
    <div class="meta-item"><span class="lbl">Participants</span><span class="val">7–8 per segment · 14–16 total</span></div>
    <div class="meta-item"><span class="lbl">Session Duration</span><span class="val">60 min (Customer) · 45 min (Associate)</span></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="page">

<!-- ═══ SECTION 1 — BACKGROUND ═══ -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">01</span><span class="section-title">Background</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <p class="para">Next plc is the UK's largest clothing retailer by sales, operating 500+ UK stores and a dominant online channel accounting for over 60% of group sales. Despite this scale, Next operates no formal loyalty programme for non-credit customers. The only existing customer reward mechanism — VIP Sale early access — is exclusively gated behind a nextpay or pay in 3 credit account, meaning the majority of Next's customer base receives no recognition, reward, or loyalty benefit for their purchasing behaviour, regardless of tenure or spend.</p>
    <p class="para">Next is planning to launch a loyalty programme that enables all customers — not just credit holders — to earn points on purchases made online, in-store, and via Click &amp; Collect, and to redeem those points for discounts and early sale access. The business also wants to enable store associates to identify and acknowledge loyal customers at the point of sale, and to drive app adoption by making the loyalty programme the primary value proposition of the Next app. The current online and in-store systems do not share customer identity data, creating a technical dependency that will need to be resolved for any cross-channel loyalty experience to function.</p>
    <p class="para">Secondary research confirms that Next's closest competitors — including M&amp;S, New Look, and H&amp;M — have active loyalty programmes that are being actively invested in and transformed. This study will establish the foundational user understanding required to design a Next loyalty experience that is grounded in real customer behaviour, mental models, and expectations — and that addresses the specific fears and anxieties (particularly around returns monitoring) that have the potential to block enrolment.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ SECTION 2 — RESEARCH GOALS ═══ -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">02</span><span class="section-title">Research Goals &amp; Collated Research Questions</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">

    <div class="goal-block">
      <div class="goal-label">Goal A · Customer Segment</div>
      <div class="goal-statement">Understand what drives repeat purchase behaviour and brand loyalty among long-tenure Next customers who shop without a nextpay credit account, so that the team can identify the motivations, habits, and relationship expectations the loyalty programme must address.</div>
      <div class="goal-rqs">
        <div class="rq-item">A1. What causes these customers to choose Next over a competitor for a specific purchase — and how consistent is that trigger across repeat visits?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">A2. To what degree do these customers feel recognised or valued by Next as a brand, and what would "being recognised" look like to them?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">A3. How do they currently experience loyalty at other retailers — which programmes have changed their behaviour, and why?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">A4. What would need to be true about a Next loyalty programme for them to actively change their shopping behaviour to earn points?</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="goal-block">
      <div class="goal-label">Goal B · Customer Segment</div>
      <div class="goal-statement">Understand how customers currently engage with loyalty programmes at other retailers — including their mental models of earn mechanics, redemption, and programme value — so that Next's programme can be designed to match or exceed the benchmarks customers already trust.</div>
      <div class="goal-rqs">
        <div class="rq-item">B1. Which loyalty programmes do these customers actively use — and what specifically makes them use one consistently versus letting another lapse?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">B2. How do they understand and track their points balances — what makes a balance feel real and worth protecting?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">B3. Do they prefer to accumulate points toward a larger reward, or receive an immediate discount — and what drives that preference?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">B4. When do they choose to redeem — and what makes a redemption moment feel satisfying versus like a poor trade?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">B5. How do they respond when a loyalty programme changes its terms — what makes the change feel acceptable versus a reason to disengage?</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="goal-block">
      <div class="goal-label">Goal C · Customer Segment</div>
      <div class="goal-statement">Understand what would drive a long-tenure Next customer to enrol in the loyalty programme and sustain engagement over time, so that the design team can prioritise the features, benefits, and trust signals that convert intent into action.</div>
      <div class="goal-rqs">
        <div class="rq-item">C1. What is the single most compelling benefit that would cause these customers to sign up immediately — and what would cause them to hesitate or decline?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">C2. What type of reward feels most valuable — discount, early access, experiential, or recognition — and does this vary by purchase type or context?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">C3. How do concerns about data privacy — particularly returns monitoring — affect their willingness to share data with a retailer loyalty programme?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">C4. What would need to be true about the mobile app experience for them to use it regularly to track and earn points?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">C5. How important is a physical card option to them personally — and who in their network would they identify as excluded by an app-only programme?</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="goal-block">
      <div class="goal-label">Goal D · Customer Segment</div>
      <div class="goal-statement">Understand customers' expectations and comfort thresholds for in-store loyalty recognition interactions, so that the design team can define the bounded data set and interaction design that feels like acknowledgement rather than surveillance.</div>
      <div class="goal-rqs">
        <div class="rq-item">D1. What does an ideal in-store recognition interaction look like — what should the associate know, say, and do?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">D2. What information about themselves are customers comfortable with a store associate seeing at the point of sale — and where is the line between recognition and discomfort?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">D3. How do they expect the in-store scan interaction to work — what is the acceptable time threshold, and what would cause them to stop using it?</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="goal-block">
      <div class="goal-label">Goal E · Store Associate Segment</div>
      <div class="goal-statement">Understand how store associates currently manage customer interactions at the point of sale — including the tools, information, and time constraints they operate within — so that any loyalty indicator can be designed to fit the real operational rhythm of a till interaction.</div>
      <div class="goal-rqs">
        <div class="rq-item">E1. Walk us through what happens from the moment a customer approaches the till to the moment they leave — what is the associate managing, in what sequence?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">E2. What information would change how they treat a customer — and what information would they never want to see at the till?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">E3. What does a difficult customer interaction look like — and what system data, if available, would have made it easier to handle?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">E4. How does queue pressure affect what they do and don't do during a transaction?</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="goal-block">
      <div class="goal-label">Goal F · Store Associate Segment</div>
      <div class="goal-statement">Understand what store associates need from a loyalty programme tool to be able to introduce it confidently to customers and use it accurately from the first day of launch, so that training and rollout can be designed for real-world associate capability and time constraints.</div>
      <div class="goal-rqs">
        <div class="rq-item">F1. What has the experience of learning and using previous in-store system changes or promotions been like — what worked and what failed?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">F2. What format and duration of training would make them feel confident introducing the loyalty programme to a customer at the till?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">F3. What would their ideal POS loyalty display look like — what would be on screen, in what order, and what would be absent?</div>
        <div class="rq-item">F4. What are the scenarios where introducing the loyalty programme would feel awkward or inappropriate — and how would they handle them?</div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ SECTION 3 — METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">03</span><span class="section-title">Methodology</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <p class="para"><strong>Method: Moderated Remote Interviews</strong></p>
    <p class="para">Moderated remote interviews are the appropriate method for this study because the research goals require deep exploration of attitudes, mental models, past behaviour, and emotional responses — not just task completion or usability assessment. The goals span motivational drivers (Goals A, B, C), interaction expectations (Goal D), operational workflow understanding (Goal E), and training readiness (Goal F), all of which require the flexibility to probe, follow unexpected threads, and adapt to each participant's specific context. A remote format enables recruitment across the UK without geographic constraint, while moderated delivery ensures the research team can pursue meaningful depth on emerging themes.</p>
    <p class="para"><strong>Session format:</strong> One researcher (moderator) + one note-taker per session. Sessions conducted via video call with screen-share capability for showing any stimulus materials if required. Sessions recorded (with participant consent) for review and synthesis.</p>
    <p class="para"><strong>Session duration:</strong> 60 minutes for Customer segment (broader goal coverage across A–D); 45 minutes for Store Associate segment (focused goals E–F with operational workflow walkthrough).</p>
    <p class="para"><strong>Team roles:</strong> Moderator (leads session, asks questions, probes); Note-taker (captures verbatim quotes, body language, timestamps for key moments); Observer (silent, Next stakeholder — optional, joins via muted video).</p>
    <p class="para"><strong>Stimuli:</strong> No prototype or task flows are involved at this stage — this is a discovery study. Moderator may share a simple concept card (programme description) for reaction probing in the final 10 minutes of Customer sessions, but this is not a usability study. Required Stimuli: One-page loyalty programme concept summary (to be prepared by research team before fieldwork).</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ SECTION 4 — PARTICIPANTS ═══ -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">04</span><span class="section-title">Participants</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">

    <!-- Segment summary table -->
    <table class="segment-summary-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Segment</th><th>User Type</th><th>Count</th><th>Session Duration</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Segment 1</strong></td><td>Next Customer (cash / debit — no nextpay)</td><td>7–8</td><td>60 minutes</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Segment 2</strong></td><td>Next Store Associate (full-time, POS role)</td><td>7–8</td><td>45 minutes</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- SEGMENT 1 — CUSTOMER -->
    <div class="segment-block">
      <span class="segment-label">Segment 1 — Customer (Cash / Debit Shopper)</span>

      <p class="para" style="font-weight:600;color:var(--navy);margin-bottom:8px;">Demographics (study-relevant only)</p>
      <ul class="criteria-list">
        <li class="criteria-item">Age 25–65, UK resident</li>
        <li class="criteria-item">Mix of gender — minimum 40% any one gender</li>
        <li class="criteria-item">Mix of in-store primary vs. online primary shoppers (at least 3 in each group)</li>
        <li class="criteria-item">No requirement on geographic location — remote delivery allows UK-wide recruitment</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="para" style="font-weight:600;color:var(--navy);margin-bottom:8px;margin-top:12px;">Qualifying Criteria</p>
      <ul class="criteria-list">
        <li class="criteria-item">Has shopped at Next (in-store or online) at least 4 times in the past 12 months using a debit card, cash, or non-Next credit card — not nextpay</li>
        <li class="criteria-item">Has been shopping at Next for at least 2 years continuously</li>
        <li class="criteria-item">Does not currently hold a nextpay or pay in 3 credit account with Next</li>
        <li class="criteria-item">Is currently an active member of at least one retail loyalty programme (e.g. Boots Advantage Card, M&amp;S Sparks, Tesco Clubcard, Nectar, Costa Club)</li>
        <li class="criteria-item">Has used a loyalty app on their smartphone to earn points or scan in-store at least once in the past 6 months</li>
        <li class="criteria-item">Has made an in-store return at a Next store at least once in the past 24 months</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="screener-block">
        <div class="screener-header">Screener Questions — Segment 1 · Customer</div>

        <div class="screener-q">
          <div class="sq-num">SQ1</div>
          <div class="sq-text">How often have you shopped at Next — either in-store or online — in the past 12 months?</div>
          <div class="sq-options">
            <div class="sq-opt">I have not shopped at Next in the past 12 months <span class="tag tag-reject">[Reject]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">1–3 times <span class="tag tag-reject">[Reject]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">4–6 times <span class="tag tag-accept">[Must Accept]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">7–12 times <span class="tag tag-accept">[Must Accept]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">More than 12 times <span class="tag tag-accept">[Must Accept]</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="screener-q">
          <div class="sq-num">SQ2</div>
          <div class="sq-text">How long have you been shopping at Next regularly?</div>
          <div class="sq-options">
            <div class="sq-opt">Less than 1 year <span class="tag tag-reject">[Reject]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">1–2 years <span class="tag tag-reject">[Reject]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">2–5 years <span class="tag tag-accept">[Must Accept]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">5–10 years <span class="tag tag-accept">[Must Accept]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">More than 10 years <span class="tag tag-accept">[Must Accept]</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="screener-q">
          <div class="sq-num">SQ3</div>
          <div class="sq-text">Which of the following do you use to pay for your Next purchases? Select all that apply.</div>
          <div class="sq-options">
            <div class="sq-opt">nextpay credit account <span class="tag tag-reject">[Reject — if selected alone or as primary]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">Pay in 3 (Next credit) <span class="tag tag-reject">[Reject — if selected alone or as primary]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">Debit card <span class="tag tag-accept">[Must Accept — if primary payment method]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">Non-Next credit card (Visa, Mastercard, Amex etc.) <span class="tag tag-accept">[Must Accept — if debit not selected]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">Cash <span class="tag tag-may">[May Accept]</span></div>
            <div class="sq-opt">PayPal / Apple Pay / Google Pay (funded by debit) <span class="tag tag-may">[May Accept]</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="screener-q">
          <div class="sq-num">SQ4</div>
